  "prompt": "How did Instagram get its first 25,000 signups?",
  "response": "Instagram, co-founded by Kevin Systrom and Mike Krieger, launched on October 6, 2010. The initial success and rapid accumulation of the first 25,000 signups can be attributed to several factors:\n\n1. **Pre-Launch Buzz:** Systrom and Krieger created anticipation and excitement before the official launch. They leveraged their networks and connections in the tech community to spread the word about the upcoming app.\n\n2. **TechCrunch Feature:** On the day of the launch, Instagram was featured on TechCrunch, a prominent technology news website. This exposure significantly boosted visibility and credibility among early adopters and tech enthusiasts.\n\n3. **Simplicity and Unique Features:** Instagram\u2019s focus on simplicity and its unique photo-sharing features with filters appealed to users who were looking for a new and engaging way to share photos. The ease of use and attractive design drew in many early users.\n\n4. **Leveraging Existing Social Networks:** Instagram allowed users to share their photos on other social networks like Facebook, Twitter, and Flickr. This integration helped users spread the word to their existing social circles, driving more signups.\n\n5. **Word of Mouth:** Early adopters of the app shared their experiences with friends and followers, creating a viral effect. Positive word of mouth played a crucial role in attracting new users.\n\n6. **Timing:** The app was launched at a time when mobile photography and social sharing were gaining popularity. Instagram tapped into this growing trend effectively, capturing the interest of users looking for new ways to enhance and share their mobile photos.\n\nThrough a combination of strategic pre-launch activities, media coverage, a compelling product, and leveraging social networks, Instagram managed to achieve rapid growth in its early days.",
